# E2E Testing Standards

Write tests that reflect exact user requirements. A failing test means a real bug — never hide it.

## Mindset: senior test automation engineer, not application developer

Write automation the way a **tester** would exercise the product: follow **real end-user flows** in order, with **explicit checks** that each step and each screen match expectations. Avoid "making the script work" with loose branching, silent skips, or merged paths that obscure what actually broke.

- GOOD: linear steps that read like a journey — sign in → land on dashboard → open feature → assert outcome
- BAD: one mega-flow that tries alternate selectors or optional steps so something always passes

## No conditional actions — anywhere in E2E code

This rule covers **all** E2E files without exception: spec files, page objects, fixture files (`workerAuth.ts`, etc.), and helpers.

Every action the automation takes must follow a **single, predetermined path**. Reading the current URL or DOM to decide which branch to execute **hides bugs** — if the app ends up in an unexpected state, the test must fail loudly, not silently take the alternate route.

- GOOD: `await this.acceptTermsAndContinue()` — always asserts the terms screen first, fails if it is missing
- BAD: `if (page.url().includes('teams/new')) { await completeWorkspace() } else { await acceptTerms() }` — a failure in one path is masked by the other
- BAD: `if (await termsHeading.isVisible()) { … }` — skips the assertion entirely when the screen is absent
- BAD: `waitForURL(url => url.includes('terms') || url.includes('teams/new'))` — encodes server-side non-determinism as "expected"
- BAD: `try { await assertOnTermsPage() } catch { await assertOnWorkspacePage() }` — swallows the failure

When a fixture helper (e.g. `registerNewAccount`) fails intermittently because the server returns unexpected state (e.g. SSR cache serving stale data), the **correct fix is to fix the server**, not to make the fixture branch around the bad state. A flaky fixture exposes a real product bug; conditional logic hides it.

## One user path per test — multiple real paths ⇒ multiple tests

If the product can reach the same **end state** through **two or more genuinely different flows** (different entry points, prerequisites, or screens in between), write **separate tests**. Each test should have its **own preconditions / setup / fixture** so it encodes a single, honest path. Different paths usually need different setup; merging them into one test with `if` / "if present" logic **hides bugs** in the path that stopped being exercised.

- GOOD: `onboarding-via-email.spec.ts` and `onboarding-via-invite-link.spec.ts`, each with setup that forces that entry
- BAD: a shared `registerUser()` that does `if (await workspacePage.isVisible()) { … } else if (await termsPage.isVisible()) { … }` — failures in one branch can still "pass" via the other
- BAD: helpers named like `completeStepIfPresent()` that skip when a screen is missing instead of failing

## Reference elements by the label the user sees in the UI

- GOOD: `getByRole('heading', { name: 'Create Custom Journey' })`
- GOOD: `getByRole('link', { name: 'Analytics' })`
- GOOD: `getByPlaceholder('Paste a YouTube link...')`
- BAD: `locator('div[data-testid="JourneysAdminContainedIconButton"]')`
- BAD: `locator('.MuiCardActionArea-root')`

## Assert exactly what the user should see — no fallbacks

If a required element is not visible, the test must FAIL and surface the bug.

- GOOD: `await expect(page.getByRole('heading', { name: 'Create Custom Journey' })).toBeVisible()`
- BAD: check visibility first and only assert if it happens to be present
- BAD: loop over multiple fallback CSS selectors
- BAD: `try/catch` that swallows an assertion failure

## Validate the destination screen before acting on it

After any navigation or step that should move the user from one screen to the next, **confirm that the new screen is actually shown** (e.g. URL, heading, or other unmistakable UI for that page) **before** clicking, filling, or asserting on elements that belong to that screen.

- GOOD: `await expect(page).toHaveURL(/expected-path/)` then `await expect(page.getByRole('heading', { name: '…' })).toBeVisible()` before further actions
- GOOD: a dedicated page-object method such as `assertOnTermsPage()` called at the start of every action block for that page
- BAD: assuming the next page loaded because the previous click resolved — interact immediately without verifying the new context

## Always use soft waits — never hard waits

ALL waiting must go through Playwright's built-in auto-waiting. There are zero exceptions in test or page-object code.

Hard waits are banned because they pause unconditionally — they make tests slow on fast machines and still flaky on slow ones. Soft waits retry until the condition is true or the timeout expires.

- GOOD: `await expect(button).toBeEnabled()` — retries until enabled
- GOOD: `await expect(dialog).toBeVisible()` — retries until visible
- GOOD: `await expect(locator).toBeHidden()` — retries until gone
- GOOD: `await page.goto(url)` — Playwright waits for navigation internally
- BAD: `await page.waitForTimeout(2000)` — unconditional pause
- BAD: `await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 1000))` — unconditional pause
- BAD: `sleep(n)` in any form
- BAD: polling loops with `setTimeout` inside tests or page objects

## Wait timeouts must be short, justified, and commented

The default timeout (30s) is enough for stable app states. Only exceed it for known slow operations (cold Vercel SSR, Apollo queries on first load, multi-step server chains). Hard limit is 90s — never set a timeout above 90000ms.

When a timeout exceeds the default, ALWAYS add an inline comment explaining why:

```typescript
// 90s: cold Vercel SSR + TeamProvider Apollo query can take >65s on first run
await expect(createButton).toBeEnabled({ timeout: 90000 })
```

- BAD: `{ timeout: 150000 }` with no comment
- BAD: `{ timeout: 60000 }` as the only value tried when it keeps failing — raise it to 90s and comment
- GOOD: `{ timeout: 30000 }` (default, no comment needed)
- GOOD: `{ timeout: 90000 }` with an inline comment explaining the slow operation

## Scope selectors to the user's visual context

Use the narrowest container that reflects what the user sees. If strict mode fires (multiple matches), that is a real data/state problem — fix the root cause, don't add `.first()`.

- GOOD: `page.locator('div[aria-label="journey-card"]', { hasText: journeyName }).getByRole('link', { name: 'Analytics' })`
- BAD: `page.locator('div[data-testid="AnalyticsItem"] a').first()`
